defaultQ1 Chair:default May I welcome members of the public to this session of the Foreign Affairs Committee? We are having a one-off evidence session on developments in 
defaultSyria
default. I am pleased to welcome our first witness—apologies if I get the pronunciation wrong—Professor 
defaultFawaz
default 
defaultGerges
default, who is professor of international law and chair in contemporary 
defaultMiddle East
default studies at the London School of Economics. Professor, welcome. It is very good of you to find time to come and see us.
default              
defaultTurning immediately to the military situation in 
defaultSyria
default, would you say that one side or the other has the upper hand militarily?
default              
defaultProfessor defaultGergesdefault:default I would argue that neither side has the capacity or the capability to deliver a decisive blow, even though I would also argue that, at this particular moment, the Syrian regime has a bit of an edge over the opposition. But while the regime is making some major tactical advances—in particular in 
defaultHoms
default, 
defaultDamascus
default, 
defaultQalamoun
default and even 
defaultAleppo
default, which surprised many of us—I do not 
defaultthink
default it can win decisively against the opposition.
default              
defaultIf we focus on the military situation in terms of the balance of power, what is most alarming to me as an observer of 
defaultSyria
default is the marginalisation of the main oppositional force in 
defaultSyria
default. Even though the balance of power has not shifted dramatically in the last two years or so, the democratic opposition, represented by the Syrian National Coalition, has not been able to make major inroads inside 
defaultSyria
default, and, most importantly, the Free Syrian Army has become more of a skeleton in the last year or so. As you know, it has lost most of its assets—the brigades that were fighting under the umbrella of the Free Syrian Army. Unfortunately for 
defaultSyria
default and the Syrian people, it has become more of a banker, providing resources and arms supplies to the various factions, but it is no longer a major fighting force inside 
defaultSyria
default.
default&#xa0;
default              
defaultQ2 Chair:default There is a proliferation of opposition groups at the moment, some armed and some unarmed. Why are they not coalescing to form a solid opposition?
default              
defaultProfessor defaultGergesdefault:default First, as you know, the opposition has been fragmented from the outset, for a variety of reasons. The opposition has been baptised by blood and fire in the last three and a half years. 
defaultSyria
default’s is one of the most repressive regimes in the 
defaultMiddle East
default, and a civil society open space hardly existed. There is a great deal of bickering among the various oppositional factions. Regional powers have also played a highly negative role in supporting certain factions and in pouring fuel on the raging fire among various oppositional factions.
default&#xa0;
default              
defaultQ3 Chair:default We are coming to regional powers in a minute, but just on the groups that are there on the ground, there is no obvious coalescence at all. Is that because of political objectives or because they have different backers?
default              
defaultProfessor defaultGergesdefault:default In the last few weeks, we have seen the emergence of the so-called 
defaultJabhat
default al-
defaultIsl
defaulta
defaultmiyyah
default, the Islamic Front, and this is one of the first major attempts on the part of the armed opposition inside 
defaultSyria
default to coalesce. The Islamic Front is made up mainly of relatively moderate 
defaultSalafi
default groups that are not affiliated with al-Qaeda-like groups, like al-
defaultNusra
default and the Islamic State in 
defaultIraq
default and al-Sham. It is the first attempt on the part of the armed opposition
default 
defaultto coalesce. The so-called Islamic Front is an umbrella under which many armed factions have coalesced. The jury is still out on whether the Islamic Front will be able not only to coalesce in terms of an organisational structure, but become an effective fighting machine inside 
defaultSyria
default.
default&#xa0;
default              
defaultQ4 Mark defaultHendrickdefault:default Coming on to the regional powers, could you give us an assessment of the extent to which the Governments of Turkey, Qatar and Saudi Arabia are assisting the anti-Assad forces in Syria?
default              
defaultProfessor defaultGergesdefault:default My take on the Syrian conflict, and I could be wrong, is that, looking at the big picture, the internal Syrian element is one of the least important now, even though this started as a political uprising—a revolution—against the Assad regime. The conflict has mutated—in fact, what we are witnessing in Syria is a fierce geo-strategic struggle between, on the one hand Saudi Arabia and its allies, and on the other hand Iran. This fierce geo-strategic struggle has major sectarian connotations. So, unfortunately for the Syrian people, 
defaultSyria
default in many ways has become more of a battlefield for regional powers. You have 
defaultSaudi Arabia
default, 
defaultQatar
default, 
defaultTurkey
default and to a lesser extent the 
defaultUnited Arab Emirates
default and 
defaultKuwait
default. On the other hand you have 
defaultIran
default and 
defaultIraq
default. 
defaultIraq
default is the most fascinating element in this equation, because, I would argue, that 
defaultIraq
default is a very important player in providing critical assets and support for the Assad regime, not to mention Hezbollah.
default              
defaultThese are really the big five powers and my take on it is that without an agreement among the regional powers, in particular between Saudi Arabia and Iran, the various Syrian groups, including the Syrian regime, would not be able to reach an agreement. That is why, at the end of the day, hardly anything would take place in Geneva II unless there is a kind of implicit agreement between 
defaultSaudi Arabia
default and 
defaultIran
default.
default&#xa0;
default              defaultQ5 Mark defaultHendrickdefault:default The question was, though, about the extent to which those Governments are assisting. I will come on to 
defaultIran
default later, but are you saying that the Turks, Qataris and Saudis, through their Governments, are heavily supporting the anti-Assad forces?
default              
defaultProfessor defaultGergesdefault:default I take it for granted that 
defaultSaudi Arabia
default is now the spearhead, supporting the so-called Islamic Front. My understanding is that the Islamic Front is basically a Saudi-supported armed coalition and 
defaultSaudi Arabia
default—in particular the Saudi intelligence services—are in charge of the Syrian portfolio now. 
defaultSaudi Arabia
default has taken over from 
defaultQatar
default in the last eight months or so. So even though initially Qatar and Turkey were the major supporters of both the political and the armed opposition, Saudi Arabia is now the spearhead and it is trying to find a kind of alternative to the al-
defaultNusra
default Front and the Islamic State in Iraq, because they are terrified that the 
defaultjihadi
default 
defaultSalafi
default groups are gaining the upper hand in some areas inside Syria.
default&#xa0;
default              defaultQ6 Mark defaultHendrickdefault:default How much non-governmental support do you think is coming from 
defaultSaudi Arabia
default, 
defaultQatar
default and 
defaultTurkey
default as well?
default              
defaultProfessor defaultGergesdefault:default You put your finger on the pulse of the really critical question why 
defaultjihadi
default 
defaultSalafi
default elements have gained the upper hand. We not only have to talk about governmental support for the various armed factions, we know a great deal of resources—private resources—are flowing from Saudi Arabia, Qatar, Kuwait, Turkey, Lebanon and other places to some of the extremist elements that have really gained momentum. Based on everything I know in terms of open sources, I do not believe that Turkey, Qatar or Saudi Arabia are funding the extremist factions inside Syria; but we know, based on multiple sources, that private individuals and businessmen are providing the assets that have enabled the 
defaultjihadi
default 
defaultSalafi
default elements to really gain the upper hand in some parts of Syria.
default&#xa0;
default              defaultQ7 Mark defaultHendrickdefault:default What sort of strength of forces are the Iranians providing, and how much co-ordination do you think there is with Hezbollah coming from 
defaultLebanon
default?
default              
defaultProfessor defaultGergesdefault:default I would argue that without 
defaultIran
default’s logistical, political and financial support, the Assad regime would not have survived as long as it has. Again, we miss the big picture by looking at how many Revolutionary Guards are inside 
defaultSyria
default; this is not about numbers. What is really most surprising about the Syrian Army is that it has not only remained an intact fighting force in the last two or three years, but it has become a deadlier fighting force in the last two and a half years. The question is why the Syrian Army has survived as long as it 
defaulthas and why it has adjusted and adapted to urban warfare. It is because of the retraining and restructuring that the Syrian Army has undergone by the Iranian Revolutionary Guards. Based on everything that we know, there has been a restructuring of the Syrian Army. If you look at the last three years or so, the army now has more capacity to go on the offensive; its fighting capabilities have increased a great deal and improved a great deal. I would argue this is in a considerable sense due to the restructuring that it has undergone by the Revolutionary Guards.
default              
defaultSecondly, when Hassan 
defaultNasrallah
default, the leader of Hezbollah, said that he made a strategic decision to intervene in 
defaultSyria
default, I had no doubt in my mind that military conditions on the ground inside 
defaultSyria
default were going to change. The question is not whether Hezbollah has sent 4,000 or 10,000 fighters. These are very skilled, determined and ideologically committed fighters. If you look at the battles in 
defaultHoms
default, in 
defaultDamascus
default and in other parts, you see that, basically, Hezbollah as a spearhead, as a vanguard force, has been able to allow the Syrian regime to achieve a certain breakthrough in the field. So yes, 
defaultIran
default and Hezbollah have made a critical difference on the battlefields inside 
defaultSyria
default in the last year or so.
default&#xa0;
default              defaultQ8default 
defaultAndrew defaultRosindelldefault:default One of the greatest concerns for people in this country is 
defaultUK
default citizens going over to 
defaultSyria
default to take part in the conflict, who potentially become radicalised and then perhaps return to the 
defaultUK
default. What do you think drives them to do this? What response should the authorities here have to this problem?
default              
defaultProfessor defaultGergesdefault:default You are asking a big question and we have to speculate a great deal. Whenever we talk about foreign fighters, we look to the 
defaultAfghanistan
default theatre, the Afghanistan-Pakistan experience. We measure everything in terms of what happened in 
defaultAfghanistan
default in the 1980s and how the Afghan war radicalised and militarised foreign fighters, some of whom returned home to 
defaultBritain
default or 
defaultSpain
default or other countries. We are talking about small numbers. The numbers that we have seen are, give or take—no-one knows the number—about 1,000 fighters from Western countries.
default&#xa0;
default              defaultQ9 Andrew defaultRosindelldefault:default In 
defaultSyria
default?
default              
defaultProfessor defaultGergesdefault:default In 
defaultSyria
default.
default&#xa0;
default              defaultQ10default 
defaultAndrew defaultRosindelldefault:default The police say that around 200 British citizens have travelled to 
defaultSyria
default for this purpose.
default              
defaultProfessor defaultGergesdefault:default I said out of the 7,000 or 8,000 foreign fighters that we think exist in 
defaultSyria
default, there are about 1,000 fighters from Europe and the 
defaultUnited States
default, two hundred of which probably are British.
default              
defaultMy take on it is that most of the fighters who have gone to 
defaultSyria
default to fight were inspired and motivated by the massacres that have been taking place inside 
defaultSyria
default. I do not think they were following Osama bin Laden’s or 
defaultAyman
default al-
defaultZawahiri’s
default call to go to 
defaultSyria
default. They were basically inspired by the massacre of the children and the mutilations—the crimes committed by the 
defaultAssad regime—in the same way that many fighters were motivated by the call to help their Afghani counterparts, co-religionists, in 
defaultAfghanistan
default.
default              
defaultThe problem is that you never know what is going to happen on a battlefield in terms of militarisation and radicalisation. My take on it is that, in the same way that many of us feared that the thousands of fighters in 
defaultIraq
default would come back to haunt European and Western societies and that did not materialise, my hope is that this will not really materialise in the case of 
defaultSyria
default either. I do not think it will, but do not take my word for it. If I were a person responsible for security in 
defaultBritain
default and 
defaultFrance
default, I would worry a great deal about what 200 or even 100 fighters returning home would do.
default&#xa0;
default              defaultQ11 Sir Menzies Campbell: defaultI a
defaultm going to ask you to speculate again, Professor, but I am quite certain that the speculation will be thoroughly informed. What do you think of the various explanations that have been offered for the use of chemical weapons on 21 August? What prompted that? Some people have suggested it was the act of a rogue commander in the middle echelon of command, others that there was a more sinister purpose. What is your take on that?
default              
defaultProfessor defaultGergesdefault:default I did a piece in the morning in 
defaultThe
default 
defaultGuardian
default, 
defaultin which I said I was surprised that the regime used chemical weapons at that particular moment, because it was gaining the upper hand. The opposition were very encircled and besieged, and also the UN team arrived. It was mind-boggling. I think the Americans say, and I take their word for it in this particular sense, that a commander wanted to clear the area, because there was a major offensive in 
defaultGhouta
default.
default 
defaultGhouta
default is an eastern suburb of 
defaultDamascus
default. The idea behind it is that operational commanders on the ground wanted to cleanse the area. According to American intelligence—you know all this stuff—they heard certain conversations in which a politician or official reprimanded one of the commanders for using chemical weapons on such a large scale. They were hoping that such use would not be detected by the international community. Again, I am citing American intelligence that officials at the highest levels knew of the chemical weapons. As you know, that was not the first time.
default&#xa0;
default              
defaultQ12 Sir Menzies Campbell:default But it was on a wholesale basis?
default              
defaultProfessor defaultGergesdefault:default Yes, because, what you need to understand is that 
defaultGhouta
default suburb is one of the most important theatres for the Assad regime. This is the gateway not only to the international airport, but to 
defaultDamascus
default. The battle for 
defaultDamascus
default is life and death for the Assad regime. This is not a tactical battle. Some elements of the regime have made it very clear that they would bring down the temple on the heads of everyone if 
defaultDamascus
default appeared to fall. This sounded a very rational explanation on the part of the commander; “This is the battle; am I going to use a limited quantity of imported chemical weapons to make the breakthrough in the 
defaultGhouta
default suburb?
default&#xa0;
default              
defaultQ13 Sir Menzies Campbell:default How far, if indeed to any extent, did that prompt Assad to accept the proposals for disarmament of chemical weapons, and how would you assess the role of Russia in that process?
default              
defaultProfessor defaultGergesdefault:default You know more than I do on this. Whatever 
defaultRussia
default wants, 
defaultRussia
default will most likely get. It is as simple as that. I talked about 
defaultIran
default; 
defaultRussia
default is more important than 
defaultIran
default in providing military hardware, diplomatic support and recognition for the Assad regime. The Russians made it very clear: there is no wiggle room here. The Foreign Minister and the President—Russians at the highest levels—wanted Assad to give up his chemical weapons, and Assad has decided to do that.
default              
defaultThe big question I would ask myself if I were Assad is: would I give up all my chemical weapons? No, I would not, because I would think, “This is a prolonged war,” and I would try to maintain a certain amount. You are talking about 1,000 tonnes of chemical weapons—who knows whether it is 1,100 tonnes of chemical weapons? Yes, on the whole, 
defaultSyria
default most likely would be disarmed of most of its chemical weapons. I myself would not give up all the chemical weapons, if I were sitting in 
defaultDamascus
default today.
default&#xa0;
default              
defaultQ14 Sir Menzies Campbell:default That is an interesting piece of evidence, because the Committee recently heard from another source the belief that Assad might have kept up to 25%.
default              
