defaultSyria
default that it doesn’t really require a wholesale political settlement in 
defaultIraq
default.
default&#xa0;
default              defaultQ42 Chair:default Moving to the chemical weapons situation, do you think that the disarmament process is weakening Assad and not making any difference at all?
default              
defaultShashank Joshi:default I think it isn’t making any difference. I think it temporarily strengthened him insofar as there was stronger 
defaultUS
default interest in continuity of government. That is, those units protecting chemical weapons, particularly specialised units of the Syrian armed forces—the 
defaultUS
default had far less interest and was inclined to see them preserved and stay in one piece. That obviously constitutes a sort of safety net for Assad. I think a lot of the criticism directed at the CW deal—the disarmament plan—was criticising the 
defaultUS
default for precluding actions 
defaultthat it was never going to take anyway. That is, for preventing it from engaging in a wholesale intervention. I mean, as we heard from Secretary of State John Kerry, it was going to be an “unbelievably small” strike. It was not going to be a regime-threatening strike. It would have targeted some elite military units and would have had a concrete impact on Assad’s effectiveness, but after that point, now that the disarmament effort is under way, I do not see why it would particularly strengthen Assad. Once the process continues, there will be less and less need for co-operation with the Assad regime anyway and he will be almost back to where he started.
default&#xa0;
default              defaultQ43 Chair:default The whole chemical weapons situation, in effect, led to the announcement that Geneva II would take place on 22 January. You mentioned 
defaultRussia
default in answer to a question from Mr 
defaultHendrick
default. Do you think we need 
defaultIran
default at the table?
default              
defaultShashank Joshi:default It depends on the point of Geneva II. If the point is to reach a comprehensive political settlement that can secure peace, you need all combatants and their supporters, which absolutely includes 
defaultIran
default. But my question would be: who in 
defaultIran
default? 
defaultIran
default is not necessarily a perfectly monolithic state. The nuclear deal was successful because the Supreme Leader empowered his President and his Foreign Minister to deal on the specific issue of the nuclear programme. On 
defaultSyria
default, there are other parts of the Iranian state that have more levers on policy, notably the Iranian 
defaultRevolutionary Guard
default. They are not going to be sitting at the table at Geneva II; it will be the Foreign Ministry. Those on the Iranian side who are able to make concessions and deal will not be attending the Geneva II process. Personally, I do not see that anything productive will come out of Geneva II next month.
default              
defaultChair:default How depressing.
default              
defaultShashank Joshi:default Look at the opposition. How can it? Six of the 
defaultIslamic Front
default’s seven groups are saying that anyone who attends from the FSA will be treated as a collaborator with Assad. You have the coalition itself saying that it will attend only under stringent conditions, including humanitarian corridors. If you want the 
defaultIslamic Front
default at the table, I just do not see the Assad regime negotiating with them. I just cannot see what comes out of this. If the purpose is much more modest—if it is only to secure tactical-level humanitarian access—I see absolutely no harm in having people around a table to discuss that.
default&#xa0;
default              
defaultQ44 Chair:default As I understand it, Geneva II is just aimed at tactical positioning.
default              
defaultShashank Joshi:default 
defaultGeneva
default I had principles of political transition, so the ultimate aim is still a political transition away from the Assad regime.
default&#xa0;
default              
defaultQ45 Mike Gapes:default May I ask you about the debate on arming the opposition? The European Union, at British and French insistence, ended its arms embargo, but it has not subsequently supplied lethal equipment to the opposition. What would have been the effect of doing so? What are the implications of the current position for the standing of the 
defaultUK
default and the other EU countries with regard to the attitude of the opposition?
default              
defaultShashank Joshi:default It depends on the level of vetting that would have been applied. President Obama signed a secret finding for the CIA to provide arms in April, but almost nothing happened for several months. The subsequent flow was an absolute trickle because the procedures for who could get the arms were so stringent. The trade-off is, the more stringent your vetting, the smaller your flow of arms. The Obama Administration’s nominee to run special operations at the Defence Department was asked about that in a congressional hearing. He was asked, “Would the 
defaultUS
default programme to train rebels at the present level make a strategic difference?” He said, “No, it wouldn’t.”
default&#xa0;
default              
defaultQ46 Mike Gapes:default What about the EU?
default              
defaultShashank Joshi:default Well, the EU would not have done so on any greater scale than the 
defaultUS
default, so there is absolutely no way that it would have made more of a difference than US supplies.
default&#xa0;
default              
defaultQ47 Mike Gapes:default What about the attitude and the perception among the opposition?
default              
defaultShashank Joshi:default Which opposition?
default&#xa0;
default              
defaultQ48 Mike Gapes:default Presumably we were not going to be arming the 
defaultal-
defaultNusra
default Front
default, but arguing for supposedly secular or moderate opposition. What is their attitude to the fact that they thought they were going to be given great assistance, particularly by the 
defaultUS
default but also by European countries, but now they are not?
default              
defaultShashank Joshi:default There was obviously a sense of embitterment, and I am sure that did persuade some proportion of the moderate opposition to move in the direction of groups such as the Islamic Front when they felt that there was going to be no serious outside support 
defaultform
default those who had suggested that there might be. However, I think they would also have been sorely disappointed by the scale at which the support would actually have occurred. Would it actually have brought sufficient good will to stave off the developments that we are now seeing? I am not so sure about that.
default&#xa0;
default              
defaultQ49 Mike Gapes:default What about the abortive decision on the air strikes, which we touched on earlier? How has that been perceived by the opposition, as well as by the Assad regime? Assad is obviously relieved because he is able to have at least another year in power while the chemical deal is concluded, but how do the opposition perceive what happened?
default              
defaultShashank Joshi:default They were furious and understandably so. They expected huge tactical opportunities opening up, particularly around 
defaultDamascus
default. The way in which the reversal occurred was seen as particularly galling, and I think that they saw this deal as having essentially legitimised Assad’s grip on power. I would not agree with all those assessments, but it would be silly to deny that they were absolutely furious.
default&#xa0;
default              
defaultQ50 Mike Gapes:default Does that make it likely that any opposition-led Syria—if there is such a thing—would be more radical and hostile to western interests than would otherwise have been the case?
default              
defaultShashank Joshi:default Possibly, but I would also say, look at Libya, where there was extensive NATO air support for rebels and many of those rebels, who were the beneficiaries of that support, are still perfectly happy to have alliances of expedience with al-Qaeda-aligned militias in the east of Libya. So, on the whole, I think it does buy good will, and we did engender some bitterness. Would it have had a huge change in attitude of the opposition beyond what would otherwise have been the case? I am not persuaded.
default&#xa0;
default              
defaultQ51 Mike Gapes:default Do you agree with Professor 
defaultGerges
default that a military strike would have been a disaster?
default              
defaultShashank Joshi:default No, I don’t agree at all. I think it could have had a powerful deterrent effect. I also think that the diplomatic solution that was reached was a sensible one.
default&#xa0;
default              
defaultQ52 Sandra Osborne:default Can I ask you about the situation in 
defaultLebanon
default and the prospect of a civil war there? How likely do you think that is and what can the 
defaultUK
default and others do to shore up the situation?
default              
defaultShashank Joshi:default It is very hard, because 
defaultLebanon
default almost asymptotically approaches civil war every year. It is particularly fragile at the moment because of this neutral sense of vulnerability. Hezbollah feels its own strongholds have been continuously attacked since May and that the rise of a Syrian opposition within 
defaultSyria
default poses dangers to it that it hasn’t seen in a long while. I think the Syrian opposition within 
defaultLebanon
default sees opportunities here as well. On the whole, everyone understands Hezbollah remains the single most powerful military actor within 
defaultLebanon
default and that a breakdown of the status quo would not necessarily mean Hezbollah falling from power, but only a messy war in which Hezbollah would once again emerge on top.
default              
defaultI am not sure that Hezbollah’s opponents really want to pull down the entire system just yet. I also think its grip on power is fairly strong. We have seen a series of pretty impressive attacks, notably the attack on the Iranian embassy in 
defaultBeirut
default, which was almost unprecedented in that sense, but it is not really threatening Hezbollah’s grip on power, in my opinion.
default              
defaultOverall, Hezbollah’s political standing within 
defaultLebanon
default has plummeted. Its cross-sectarian appeal has plummeted—it is seen more and more as a sectarian actor than it ever was, particularly compared with how it was in 2006, when it was seen to resist Israeli aggression by many segments of Lebanese society. So it is severely weakened, but I am not sure that I would predict a civil war within the next year or so in 
defaultLebanon
default.
default&#xa0;
default              
defaultQ53 Sandra Osborne:default What about the situation with refugees from 
defaultSyria
default? 
defaultLebanon
default, in particular, but other neighbouring countries already support quite high numbers of refugees, including the Palestinians. What is going to happen with that in the longer term? How sustainable is that for the foreseeable future?
default              
defaultShashank Joshi:default It poses a lot of risks, particularly radicalisation within those camps. If they come to be seen as sources of support for Sunni extremists by Hezbollah, you could see some pretty messy conflicts emerge. Hezbollah is already very concerned about hitting back at what it sees as Sunni areas of support in parts of 
defaultLebanon
default. They could easily become more militarised. They could easily become sources of extremism, radicalisation and militancy. From a purely humanitarian point of view, the more the fighting escalates around places like 
defaultDamascus
default, the greater these flows will become. The Lebanese state is not in a position to provide adequate care for these groups over the longer term. We have known that for a while and the same is true in 
defaultJordan
default as well. So that is not a new development as such.
default&#xa0;
default              defaultChair:default Thank you very much for coming along. As ever, your evidence is to the point. We really appreciate it and hope we can call on your services again.
default              
defaultShashank Joshi:default 
defaultOf course, you’re welcome.
